prefix: Approach the following question the way someone in high school would.
problem_prompt: Approach the following question the way someone in high school would. Jenna collects stamps.  She puts the same number of stamps on each page and then inserts each page into one of her two stamp books.  One of her stamp books has a total of 840 stamps.  The other has 1008.  What is the largest number of stamps that Jenna could be putting on each page?
solution: The number of stamps Jenna puts on each page must divide the number of stamps she puts into each book, so the largest possible number of stamps she puts on each page is gcd$(840, 1008) = \boxed{168}$.

The factors of 1008 are: 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 7, 8, 9, 12, 14, 16, 18, 21, 24, 27, 28, 36, 42, 48, 56, 63, 72, 84, 112, 126, 144, 168, 189, 252, 336, 378, 504, 756, 1008

The largest number that appears in both lists is 168. Therefore, Jenna could be putting 168 stamps on each page.
